article.description: Jalen Rose scored 27 points and Jamal Crawford added a season-high 24 and 10 assists as the Chicago Bulls handed the Lakers just their second defeat in 11 games, 116-99.
article.headline: Bulls show plenty of the promise of youth

images.name: Oneal_Shaquille 030311 Inline
images.caption: Shaquille O'Neal took the blame for "making the Bulls' season" with subpar his outing.

article.linkText: Youth movement: Bulls blow away Lakers
article.story:
CHICAGO (AP) -- So this is what the Chicago Bulls' youth movement is supposed to look like. Jamal Crawford led the Baby Bulls with a career-high 24 points and 10 assists, and Eddy Curry scored 20 while shutting down Shaquille O'Neal as Chicago stunned the Los Angeles Lakers 116-99 Tuesday night. Tyson Chandler had 12 rebounds for the Bulls, who have now beaten the Lakers in three of their last four meetings. "It definitely is a preview of what they wanted,'' said veteran Jalen Rose, who had 27 points and seven assists. "The way the young guys played today shows why they had the draft status they had, and it shows why there are the expectations for them that there are.'' Los Angeles sure didn't look like a team that had won nine of 10 games as it made the first stop on a five-game road trip that includes four games in five nights. Kobe Bryant had 36 and Rick Fox scored a season-high 23, but they didn't get much help. O'Neal was held to 13 points and 10 rebounds as the Lakers were outrebounded 45-38. "We made their year,'' O'Neal said. "I'm going to take the blame for that game. I had a slow night. I missed a lot of shots and really couldn't get into it.'' Give the young Bulls credit for that. While Bryant and O'Neal were getting off to a slow start, the Bulls were showcasing the aggressiveness and athleticism the team hopes will someday translate into championships. They shot 80 percent from 3-point range and 55 percent from the floor, and had a 16-10 advantage on second-chance points. Crawford set the tone with 12 points on 5-of-6 shooting in the first quarter, and the Bulls never looked back as they went up by as many as 17 in the first half. "(O'Neal) seemed like he was a little out of sync to start the game,'' Bryant said. "So we tried to get him the ball, get him some touches. But Chicago did a good job, pretty much ignoring everybody else and trying to keep the ball out of his hands.'' But Bryant and the Lakers finally got rolling with a 19-7 run that spanned halftime. O'Neal scored on a monster dunk, Fox hit a 3 and Bryant made a free throw to cap the spurt, pulling Los Angeles to 67-64 with 8:07 left in the third. "That is part of the learning,'' Chicago coach Bill Cartwright said. "We want them to continue to handle situations, handle runs, have poise -- and a lot of those things are learning.'' And, on this night at least, the Bulls were quick studies. Crawford coolly drilled a 3, and Curry scored on a follow-up dunk to end the threat. "I do feel we play better because we're scared,'' Rose said. "They're the three-time world champions and have two of the best players in the world. If you're not, you can get blown away.'' Los Angeles got close again on Bryant's driving layup, pulling within 76-70 with 5:31 left in the third. But after a timeout, the Bulls went on a run that brought back memories of the old days in Chicago. Marshall hit a 3-pointer, Curry scored on a dunk and Rose hit a 3 that brought the United Center crowd to its feet and gave Chicago an 84-70 lead with 3:29 left in the third. "We ran into a good team tonight,'' said Lakers coach Phil Jackson, who has lost his last two games against his former team. "We just didn't match their energy at all. I guess I can write it off to the time zone changes.'' The Bulls extended their lead to 19 midway through the fourth on a 3-pointer and fast-break layup from Jay Williams, but the Lakers had one last run in them. Samaki Walker scored on a hook shot to start a 15-3 spurt that pulled Los Angeles within 103-96 with 3:01 to play. But Rose drilled a 16-footer, Crawford hit a short jumper with two minutes left and the Lakers never threatened again. "If we can do this against a team like the Lakers, we should be able to do this against anyone,'' Curry said. "When we play together, we can be a dangerous team.''

Game notes
Fox's eight 3-point attempts in the first set a record for a Bulls opponent in a single quarter. ... Curry has now scored 20 or more points in three straight games. ... O'Neal's three field goals tied his season low. ... Chicago is 10-1 when shooting 50 percent or better from the field.
